the ends, may be double in length to that which
$hould be fa$tned in the Wall, that is $u$tained at but
one end.</I></P>
<P>Which of it $elt is very obvious; for if we $hall $up-
po$e of the Cylinder which I de$cribe A B C, its
half A B to be the utmo$t Length that is able to be
$u$tained, being fa$tened at the end B, it $hall be $u$tained in the
$ame manner, if being laid upon the Fulciment G, it $hall be
counterpoi$ed by its other half B C. And likewi$e, if of the Cy-
linder D E F, the Length $hall be $uch that onely one half of it
can be $u$tained, being fa$tened at the end D, and con$equent-
ly the other E F, fixed at the end F; it is manife$t, that placing
the Fulciments H and I under the ends D and F, every Moment
